l as being almost illiterate, being 'dumped' in a class of 25-30 pupils with no support. That's because it's far cheaper to place pupils in a mainstream secondary than in a specialist unit with all the facilities and specially trained staff. &#10;It's very sad that their education, as well as sometimes the education of their classmates, being ruined due to cost cutting. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="676" language="en" documentId="4908" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Clare B(469)" date="02-04-10 20:08" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://www.netmums.com/coffeehouse/general-coffeehouse-chat-514/news-current-affairs-topical-discussion-12/405944-special-needs-children-mainstream-schools-all.html" topic="mainstreaming" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="4908" notes="" title="Special Needs children in Mainstream Schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="549"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="550" end="676"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>